  "prompt": "What will be the derivative of x|x|, if x is -1",
  "response": "Let $f(x) = x|x|$.\nWhen $x \\geq 0$, $|x| = x$, so $f(x) = x^2$ for $x \\geq 0$.\nWhen $x < 0$, $|x| = -x$, so $f(x) = x(-x) = -x^2$ for $x < 0$.\nTherefore, we can write $f(x)$ as\n$$\nf(x) = \\begin{cases} x^2 & \\text{if } x \\geq 0 \\\\ -x^2 & \\text{if } x < 0 \\end{cases}\n$$\nWe want to find the derivative of $f(x)$ at $x = -1$. Since $x < 0$, we have $f(x) = -x^2$.\nThen, the derivative is\n$$\nf'(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} (-x^2) = -2x\n$$\nAt $x = -1$,\n$$\nf'(-1) = -2(-1) = 2\n$$\nAlternatively, we can express $f(x)$ as $x|x|$.\n$$\nf(x) = x|x| = \\begin{cases} x^2 & \\text{if } x \\geq 0 \\\\ -x^2 & \\text{if } x < 0 \\end{cases}\n$$\nThe derivative of $f(x)$ is\n$$\nf'(x) = \\begin{cases} 2x & \\text{if } x \\geq 0 \\\\ -2x & \\text{if } x < 0 \\end{cases}\n$$\nWe can rewrite this as $f'(x) = 2|x|$.\nWhen $x = -1$, $f'(-1) = 2|-1| = 2(1) = 2$.\n\nNow, we write out the argument and find the final answer.\nLet $f(x) = x|x|$. We want to find the derivative of $f(x)$ at $x = -1$.\nSince $x = -1 < 0$, we have $|x| = -x$.\nThus, for $x < 0$, $f(x) = x|x| = x(-x) = -x^2$.\nTaking the derivative with respect to $x$, we have\n$$\nf'(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} (-x^2) = -2x\n$$\nAt $x = -1$, we have\n$$\nf'(-1) = -2(-1) = 2\n$$\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{2}$",
